segments.text: And she didn't give it up for a long time.
She had a roper with a gas stove with an oven on it.
So that was when we were uptown then.
Alright, your freshman year went okay.
Do you remember what you did at the end of that summer after you were a freshman?
I don't know whether it'd be 33.
Most likely we went to Indianapolis.
So you traveled?
We traveled.
All right.
Because Dad had to go to, he was Secretary and Treasurer and the insurance business was a big part of that.
Was it better to be a sophomore at A&M than to be a freshman?
It didn't make a difference to me.
It didn't?
How did your routine in the Corps change?
Well, see, I quit the Corps in... Well, but you were in it two years.
Two years, well, no.
I was a day duck, and they just tolerated me.
About how many day ducks were there, I reckon?
There was probably not more than 15, so there were not very many.
And the...
The only way you'd get out would be to have had previous military service.
Or you couldn't qualify.
Or you lived near the campus.
No.
Oh.
Well, the only way you'd get out of the military.
Oh, oh, oh, the military.
Was those two.
It was to have previous service or
you couldn't make the physical specifications.
But though you could be a day duck if you lived in the community, couldn't you?
Yeah.
You didn't change your major, you stayed with that.
Did you ever think about changing your major?
Were there some special courses you had as a sophomore?
Some special people?
Oh yeah, we had one I remember was in, what would you call it, about genes in people and animals.
See, I'd take a bunch of courses about cattle
even chickens and things like that.
We had to do that and rinse with the cattle.
And then, what do you call it?
They had a special, they did nothing but teach that.
Genetics?
Genetics.
genetics.
And I enjoyed that.
I enjoyed that.
Did you ever have a chemistry course from M.T.
Harrington?
No, I had it from... No.
I knew him.
I knew him.
Describe him.
Tall fella.
I always thought...
Pleasant personality?
Yeah.
He always...
He always talked.
I always remembered who I was.
And Mrs. Harrington always a lady?
I never did have a lot of contact with her, but I knew who she was.
While you were an A&M undergraduate, were there any students here whose parents were famous, rich, important?
No, but in Tarleton I did.
Who?
I don't know who they were.
Oh.
I taught, see I taught ag engineering in Tarleton from 35 to 37 for two years.
And I taught and had to teach farm shop, all the ag engineering courses, what they had that they wanted, and
So I was in that farm shop, and we had a lot of kids that came from the western part out there.
And this young man, he knew what he was doing.
And so I just asked him, I said, son, how big a farm do you have?
He said, we got a small one.
ranch 24-6.
Describe the student body when you were a student here.
Describe the A&M student body.
Where were they from?
What kinds of families?
What kinds of attitudes?
They brought a whole bunch of people in.
All the... Well, they had some what they called co-op houses.
Now those were real good pieces.
That was real good.
Because what that did
That brought a lot of people to A&M that never would have gotten here in the first place.
And what it did, now, one of my, one of the, we had, there were five of us that really were in A&M.
And Thompson was one of them.
but he couldn't get the mass, so he went into agriculture.
But his mother, they were from Throckmorton.
Throckmorton.
They came from Throckmorton County.
And she ran the house.
The co-op house.
And they shipped in
All sorts of food.
Everything that they could, you know.
And they tried to keep them again.
And you could get a pretty good job around here at 25 cents an hour.
And make some money.
I know I made enough to pay my way all the way through.
All the fees.
In general, was the typical student body, were there some city boys and country boys?
They had some city people in them.
From where primarily?
What cities?
I don't know.
We didn't make much difference about that.
Most of them were plain old boys that come off the farm.
And...
Was there a variety of their backgrounds, of their ancestry, and where they went to church?
Were there some German boys and Catholic boys and Lutheran boys?
All of those people put in these places they've got up here for, you know, the Methodists.
They have one there.
I know the Baptists do, and the Lutherans do too.
And the Catholics, I think they have one up there.
But they kept houses open for the students, even though they were in the dormitory.
In terms of attitude, would we have said they were liberal or conservative?
Very conservative.
Hardworking?
Hardworking.
But they're all Democrats.
Well, in that day, there weren't any Republicans around here.
That's right.
And you know why, don't you?
Franklin Roosevelt.
No.
In my family, I know why.
No.
My family thought Franklin Roosevelt saved the country.
Well, I didn't think much of his domestic product.
They took the job of resettlement three years up in Dallas.
But what got me was when I read a book called Marching Orders by Lee.
And they described Roosevelt in there.
And he was the guy in line behind all of that military.
He was the one that took
He really did a job there.
But now the other reason is the treatment we got after the Civil War.
Oh, yes.
I agree.
The parents and grandparents.
Yeah, but you see the Negroes got into the Republican Party.
And so everybody else was a Democrat.
That's right.
But the Democrats we get, except for a few, which I know is the yellow... Yellow dog.
Yellow dog Democrats.
They're the ones way off on the side.
But if you take the regular ones, they're nothing but Republicans.
And that's why the change over here recently has been
So complete.
Yes.
Back to the student body.
Were there any rich kids?
Oh, yeah.
In terms of being accepted, did any of those differences matter to being an Aggie at that point?
Why was everybody so accepted?
That's a key part of A&M.
Why was that?
Well,
They beat the hell out of you.
Was it also that everybody went through some of the same experiences?
That's right.
That's right.
They're all in it together.
Do you remember many people dropping out of school?
Oh, yeah.
Were those the separator courses?
No, chemistry.
Chemistry separated a bunch of them.
The biggest thing we've got so far is blend.
We can sell it.
When did you start using your slide rule?
When you were taught it.
When?
When you were a freshman.
Right, but you didn't use one in high school?
No.
And do you remember when you got yours?
Yeah, still got it.
It's a duplex love load.
And did you wear it on your belt proudly?
Yeah.
Was that a kind of a mark of an engineer?
Yeah, you had to have it.
It's a kind of a...
It's the equivalent of today's computer.
It is a computer.
Sure, sure.
I've got one that's even better.
How much is that?
It's a big one like that, circular.
Oh, yes.
Now, for when you're in the fan business, like I was for 60 years, you just flip it around.
I mean, it'll do what this thing does.
Now, in athletics, you guys went to Kyle Field.
Was DeWare Fieldhouse already here when you were a student?
When was it built?
I would think in the early 20s.
Oh, but when you were an undergraduate, when you were a student here, it was...
Already built.
Describe going to games, you and your buddies, when y'all went to game in DeWare Fieldhouse.
Oh, I don't know.
It was just a big old place.
Did y'all make noise?
Oh, yeah.
What were the yell-eaters like then?
Boy, they were something.
They were, they were some, and they were picked out right.
They were picked out right.
You had, and you had, that student organization was set up by the, by the military.
And those officers, those military officers made that thing run.
And I'll give you an example of it.
You know they got this march to the river that they did there?
You know what ever happened before?
I don't see it.
It happened in those dormitories across from the Y.
There were 32 of them in there.
And Major Sloan was the
officer in charge.
And he was from the Naval Academy.
He wasn't from, he was from the Naval Academy.
But he couldn't go aboard ship.
He couldn't, he just couldn't make it.
So they transferred him to the artillery.
She was a good woman, but tough too.
They all are.
And so they would have had a big fling ding up there in that courtyard in between that thing.
They were just raising all kinds of hell.
And the major went up there and, oh, somebody called him.
We called a major, and so he went up there.
He told the cadet officers to quiet this thing down and let's get it in order.
And he just, that's all he did.
He just issued an order and walked off.
And so they didn't.
And so somebody called him again.
And he walked up there and he said, he told those student officers, fall out, all of them, everything.
He called them out.
He marched those kids in formation all the way to the river.
That's where that got started.
That's where it got started.
And that would have been about when?
During your student years?
Yeah, it might have been.
It probably was, it probably was.
And so that's where they really got, and he marched and turned them around, marched them back.
They got back ready in time to go to breakfast.
When you were a student, did the Corps ever do anything that was rebellious?
Did they ever march on the president's house?
No.
The only time they ever did anything, there were a couple of times.
Well, you've got another problem, too.
In World War I, you could go to A&M for $1.
You knew that, didn't you?
I'd heard that.
You could.
They paid all the fees.

but you had to give your you had to pay your I don't know if you had to give them the housing or not but you had to pay your bail and there were those two buildings that were in front of the main building there were two there and every one of those guys came back with a .45 and on top of
The dome is a hook like this.
With a light.
1,500 watts.
Prexy's moon.
Yeah.
So what they did, you could walk into that one on that side and just push the screen open like that, and you could take that old .45 and take a shot at it.
And you could fire one shot.
at that thing, and there was a hell of a lot of holes.
But that, and then they marked it on the wall.
You just put a mark like this, and they marked four of them, scratches off this one.
I walked into many of those rooms up there.
They knocked it out every other night.
Oh, really?
Oh, so they did, they were successful.
The last time I saw that tried was in 1935.
A company that I saw, they marched up there.
And a guy took a Springfield and tried to hit it.
That's the last time I ever saw that.
Because one day in Mr.
Rudder's office, he mentioned that he had tried when he was a student here.
And I believe he's class of 32.
To knock it out?
Yeah, and he said that that was a very risky thing to do, but you thought it was really good to shoot at it one time.
Yeah, but you always shot it with a .45.
They used the rifle in the last one.
And another thing that happened was that they had a problem with the flag on the flagpole.
So you see that flag on that flagpole?
The original one, I think they changed the flag.
It was pipe.
It had big joints in it.
And the one guy said he could climb it.
See, they just cut the rope right below the leg hole.
And so it
went up.
And so they, this must have been back quite a while, because they came to me, we used to have kite fights in Simpson Field.
And everybody had a kite, some pretty good size.
And some of the students knew it and then some of the people there
They were trying to get that flag down.
It was some, I don't know, it wasn't a U.S. flag or any kind of flag.
It was somebody's riding on it.
So they asked me if I could fly a kite up there.
Or they would get me a kite.
Or could I build a kite?
So I built a couch for them.
I built a kite and put a big old tail on the end of it.
And they filled it for the hooks, fishhooks.
They got it.
Really?
That's the way they got it.
And this was about when?
Were you a student then?
No, I was a student.
Oh.
That was when I was in high school.
You were still in high school.
Or in grade school, I think.
But we used to have pretty good guidance like that.
And Fermier, a kid named Fermier, his father and mother died here.
And he was left here all by himself.
That was a terrible story.
His father went, Fermier was his name.
His father, his wife died.
And so the only way you could

uh send a telegram was to go down to this uh where there was railroad across there was a tower and they kept people up there and that was connected to the western union that's the only place you could see him and so uh he uh
He went there and got all the writing done for them to send out, and then he just slumped over.
My, my, my.
That is awful.
He was a faculty member?
He was head of the ME department.
Oh, my.
His name was Fermier.
I've heard that name.
That happens.
So you know, you know.
While you were a student, do you remember any tragic events involving other students?
Oh, they used to have some problems with, I know one student got killed trying to, but he was killed right up there by the entrance of the college.
they were hauling logs or something, or something like that.
He got killed right there.
That was with the bonfire.
But none of the, and during your years, none of the presidents died of heart attacks or anything like that?
No close family friend?
No, no close family friend.
What about happy times?
What about some happy memories from your student days?
Well, you didn't have any radio, no TV, so you went and played.
Dean Bones' office in front of his yard, there'd be five or ten of us out there playing with each other.
It might have been some sort of ball or something like that, but it was not really organized.
When, as far as you remember, when did your family get a telephone at home?
In College Park?
Did you all have one on the campus in your home?
Yes.
Oh, you did?
Okay.
So you had a telephone early?
We had a telephone early, yeah.
Okay.
The number was 125.
And was it a private line or a party line?
Party line.
Okay.
All you had to do was just call up there, 125, please.
And you did it.
Now, on the college, when we moved off after World War II, it took a long time to get a phone.
Oh, sure, sure.
We had to tell that repairman that there was a bunch of money under that.
Let's go back to hitchhiking.
Share some of your hitchhiking stories.
Some of your happiest and least happy.
The only time I ever did hitchhiking really was coming back from Brookings.
That was interesting.
It was really interesting.
So you wore your Aggie uniform all the way back from the Dakotas.
Yeah.
But you didn't hitchhike going from here to Houston?
No, we had cars.
Okay.
Okay.
Well, our family always had cars.
We had the old Huffmobile.
We had a 21 Dodge.
Then we changed to the Model A.
We had four of those.
And then we had the first 1932 Ford that ever came into town.
Ned got it.
And then we went 33s, 34s.
And when I, in 35, I bought a 35.
We had a 35 Oldsmobile.
We had, and then we started on the, and then we got a 30,
six automobile coupe.
What was your favorite of all those cars?
Oh, a Ford man.
I don't care what it is.
The what?
A Ford man.
A Ford man?
That's a Ford man.
The others, all of those mobiles up to the more modern ones,
I had at the 41 and the remains of it are still sitting on the farm out there.
I always have wished I had a about a 31 four-door Model A so I could carry four adults in it.
I've always thought that would be great but I don't have the skill to repair it and I don't know who today
I can fix it.
But who else could?
There aren't any of these young mechanics who wouldn't know how to do that.
Well, if you get a good one and you get it cleaned up and it's right, you ain't got no problem for a long time.
It'd be good.
Now, during the Depression, though, a bunch of Aggies, a lot of Aggie students must have been very short on money.
And so they had jobs on the campus.
What else did they do to try to economize?
Mostly they worked with the college.
You see, they had student labor.
And the college had an awful lot of funds for student labor.
When some of the Aggies had out-of-town dates,
Did any of them ever stay at your home?
I've heard that some of the campus families.
They would arrange with their date to stay with somebody else.
That's correct.
It was a family affair.
The whole college was a family affair.
Elaborate on that.
Well, if the head of the department
He had an obligation to go see, well, first off, the first thing Dad did when he got here, he got H.P.
Smith somehow.
He got F.R.
Jones somehow.
You probably know F.R.
And then he got Pete Mumford.
He got another fellow by the name of,
